  "answer": "## Answer\nAutonomous agents are the better fit when the work is open-ended, ambiguous, or needs dynamic tool selection; workflow-based agents are the better fit when you need fixed paths, auditability, and bounded execution. OpenAI recommends starting with a single agent or workflow and only adding complexity when the problem justifies it, while Anthropic’s guide explicitly frames workflows as static/predictable and agentic systems as more dynamic. `https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/` `https://resources.anthropic.com/hubfs/Building%20Effective%20AI%20Agents-%20Architecture%20Patterns%20and%20Implementation%20Frameworks.pdf` ([openai.com](https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/))\n\n### Required aspect coverage\n- flexibility: Autonomous agents are more flexible for ambiguous, open-ended work; workflows are less flexible but easier to standardize. `https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/` ([openai.com](https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/))\n- controllability: Workflow-based agents give tighter control via predefined paths, typed inputs/outputs, preview/debug tools, and handoffs; autonomous agents trade some of that control for adaptive behavior. `https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-builder` ([platform.openai.com](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-builder))\n- observability: Workflows are easier to observe because traces record model calls, tool calls, guardrails, and handoffs; OpenAI also recommends building observable systems from day one. `https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-evals` ([platform.openai.com](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-evals))\n- cost: More autonomous/multi-agent setups can consume substantially more tokens and coordination overhead, while structured workflows make execution costs easier to estimate. `https://resources.anthropic.com/hubfs/Building%20Effective%20AI%20Agents-%20Architecture%20Patterns%20and%20Implementation%20Frameworks.pdf` ([resources.anthropic.com](https://resources.anthropic.com/hubfs/Building%20Effective%20AI%20Agents-%20Architecture%20Patterns%20and%20Implementation%20Frameworks.pdf))\n- reproducibility: Versioned workflow snapshots plus trace graders/datasets make workflow runs easier to replay and compare consistently. `https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-builder` `https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-evals` ([platform.openai.com](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-builder))\n- failure recovery: Agents can halt and hand control back to the user on failure, and newer SDK support can resume from checkpoints if the environment fails or expires. `https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/` `https://openai.com/index/the-next-evolution-of-the-agents-sdk/` ([openai.com](https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/))\n\n## Sources\n1. OpenAI, *A practical guide to building agents* — `https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/` ([openai.com](https://openai.com/business/guides-and-resources/a-practical-guide-to-building-ai-agents/))\n2. OpenAI, *Agent Builder* — `https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/agent-builder` ([platform.openai.com](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-builder))\n3. OpenAI, *Evaluate agent workflows* — `https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/agent-evals` ([platform.openai.com](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agent-evals))\n4. OpenAI, *The next evolution of the Agents SDK* — `https://openai.com/index/the-next-evolution-of-the-agents-sdk/` ([openai.com](https://openai.com/index/the-next-evolution-of-the-agents-sdk))\n5. OpenAI, *From model to agent: Equipping the Responses API with a computer environment* — `https://openai.com/index/equip-responses-api-computer-environment/` ([openai.com](https://openai.com/index/equip-responses-api-computer-environment/))\n6. Anthropic, *Building Effective AI Agents: Architecture Patterns and Implementation Frameworks* — `https://resources.anthropic.com/hubfs/Building%20Effective%20AI%20Agents-%20Architecture%20Patterns%20and%20Implementation%20Frameworks.pdf` ([resources.anthropic.com](https://resources.anthropic.com/hubfs/Building%20Effective%20AI%20Agents-%20Architecture%20Patterns%20and%20Implementation%20Frameworks.pdf))\n\n## Limitations\nThe trade-off summary is a synthesis, not a universal benchmark: exact cost, observability, and recovery behavior depend on the model, tool stack, and workload. The strongest cost claims are provider guidance, not a universal constant. The case-study evidence is from a single vendor/customer example and may not generalize to every deployment. ([resources.anthropic.com](https://resources.anthropic.com/hubfs/Building%20Effective%20AI%20Agents-%20Architecture%20Patterns%20and%20Implementation%20Frameworks.pdf))"
